# Codebase to PDF Program

I'll help you create a program that can convert a codebase into a PDF document. This can be useful for code reviews, documentation, or sharing code in a more structured format.

Let's break down what we'll need to build:

1. A way to traverse the file system to find code files
2. A mechanism to read the content of these files
3. A PDF generation library to create the output document
4. Configuration options for customization (file types to include, formatting, etc.)

## First Steps

We need to select a PDF generation library for Java. Popular options include:

- iText
- Apache PDFBox
- OpenPDF (fork of iText)

Let's explore what's current and best suited for our needs:# Creating a Codebase to PDF Program in Java

Based on your request to create a program that converts a codebase to PDF, I'll outline a solution using modern Java libraries that can properly format source code in PDF documents.

## Recommended Libraries

For this project, we'll need a reliable PDF generation library that can handle code formatting with proper syntax highlighting. Based on current information, these are the best options:

1. **iText** - A powerful, open-source Java PDF library [[1]](https://sourceforge.net/directory/pdf-generation-libraries/)
2. **Apache PDFBox** - An open-source Java library for PDF document creation and manipulation
3. **OpenPDF** - A free fork of iText with LGPL and MPL licenses [[7]](https://github.com/LibrePDF/OpenPDF)
4. **Flying Saucer with iText** - Good for converting HTML+CSS to PDF [[1]](https://pdforge.com/blog/top-java-libraries-for-pdf-generation-in-2025)

## Proposed Approach

For a codebase to PDF converter, I recommend a solution that:

1. Recursively scans the codebase directory
2. Identifies source code files
3. Applies syntax highlighting (converting code to HTML with highlighting)
4. Renders the highlighted code to PDF

## Project Architecture

Let's design a simple program with these components:

1. **FileScanner** - Traverses directories to find code files
2. **SyntaxHighlighter** - Converts code to HTML with syntax highlighting
3. **PDFGenerator** - Creates the final PDF document
4. **Main** - Coordinates the process

## Sample Implementation

Here's how we can start building this project:

### 1. First, let's update your Main class:

```java
import java.io.File;
import java.nio.file.Path;
import java.nio.file.Paths;
import java.util.List;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Default path if none provided
            String path = ".";
            String outputFile = "codebase.pdf";

            // Parse command line arguments if provided
            if (args.length >= 1) {
                path = args[0];
            }
            if (args.length >= 2) {
                outputFile = args[1];
            }

            System.out.println("Starting codebase to PDF conversion...");
            System.out.println("Source directory: " + path);
            System.out.println("Output file: " + outputFile);

            // Create components
            FileScanner scanner = new FileScanner();
            SyntaxHighlighter highlighter = new SyntaxHighlighter();
            PDFGenerator pdfGenerator = new PDFGenerator();

            // Scan for code files
            List<File> codeFiles = scanner.scanDirectory(Paths.get(path));
            System.out.println("Found " + codeFiles.size() + " code files.");

            // Generate PDF
            pdfGenerator.generatePDF(codeFiles, highlighter, outputFile);

            System.out.println("PDF generation complete! Output saved to: " + outputFile);

        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.err.println("Error generating PDF: " + e.getMessage());
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Create a FileScanner class:

```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Path;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;
import java.util.stream.Stream;

public class FileScanner {

    // File extensions to include
    private final List<String> codeExtensions = List.of(
        ".java", ".py", ".js", ".ts", ".html", ".css", ".c", ".cpp", 
        ".h", ".cs", ".go", ".rs", ".php", ".rb", ".kt", ".swift"
    );

    // Directories to exclude
    private final List<String> excludeDirs = List.of(
        "node_modules", "target", "build", "dist", ".git", ".idea", 
        "venv", "__pycache__", "bin", "obj"
    );

    public List<File> scanDirectory(Path directory) throws IOException {
        try (Stream<Path> pathStream = Files.walk(directory)) {
            return pathStream
                .filter(Files::isRegularFile)
                .filter(this::isCodeFile)
                .filter(path -> !isInExcludedDir(path))
                .map(Path::toFile)
                .collect(Collectors.toList());
        }
    }

    private boolean isCodeFile(Path path) {
        String fileName = path.toString().toLowerCase();
        return codeExtensions.stream().anyMatch(fileName::endsWith);
    }

    private boolean isInExcludedDir(Path path) {
        return excludeDirs.stream()
            .anyMatch(dir -> path.toString().contains(File.separator + dir + File.separator));
    }
}
```

### 3. Create a SyntaxHighlighter class:

```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.nio.file.Files;
import java.nio.file.Path;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class SyntaxHighlighter {

    // Map file extensions to language names
    private final Map<String, String> languageMap = new HashMap<>();

    public SyntaxHighlighter() {
        // Initialize language mappings
        languageMap.put(".java", "Java");
        languageMap.put(".py", "Python");
        languageMap.put(".js", "JavaScript");
        languageMap.put(".ts", "TypeScript");
        languageMap.put(".html", "HTML");
        languageMap.put(".css", "CSS");
        // Add more as needed
    }

    public String highlightCode(File file) throws IOException {
        String content = Files.readString(file.toPath());
        String extension = getFileExtension(file.getName());
        String language = languageMap.getOrDefault(extension, "plaintext");

        // In a real implementation, we would use a proper syntax highlighting library
        // For now, we'll use a simple HTML wrapper
        String htmlContent = "<pre><code class=\"language-" + language + "\">" +
                escapeHtml(content) +
                "</code></pre>";

        return htmlContent;
    }

    private String getFileExtension(String filename) {
        int lastDotIndex = filename.lastIndexOf('.');
        if (lastDotIndex > 0) {
            return filename.substring(lastDotIndex).toLowerCase();
        }
        return "";
    }

    private String escapeHtml(String content) {
        return content
            .replace("&", "&amp;")
            .replace("<", "&lt;")
            .replace(">", "&gt;")
            .replace("\"", "&quot;")
            .replace("'", "&#39;");
    }
}
```

### 4. Create a PDFGenerator class using iText:

```java
import java.io.File;
import java.io.FileOutputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.List;

import com.itextpdf.text.Document;
import com.itextpdf.text.DocumentException;
import com.itextpdf.text.Font;
import com.itextpdf.text.FontFactory;
import com.itextpdf.text.PageSize;
import com.itextpdf.text.Paragraph;
import com.itextpdf.text.pdf.PdfWriter;
import com.itextpdf.tool.xml.XMLWorkerHelper;
import java.io.StringReader;

public class PDFGenerator {

    public void generatePDF(List<File> files, SyntaxHighlighter highlighter, String outputFile) 
            throws IOException, DocumentException {

        Document document = new Document(PageSize.A4, 50, 50, 50, 50);
        PdfWriter writer = PdfWriter.getInstance(document, new FileOutputStream(outputFile));
        document.open();

        // Add a title
        Font titleFont = FontFactory.getFont(FontFactory.HELVETICA_BOLD, 16);
        document.add(new Paragraph("Codebase Documentation", titleFont));
        document.add(new Paragraph(" "));

        // Add table of contents
        addTableOfContents(document, files);

        // Process each file
        for (File file : files) {
            try {
                // Add file name as heading
                Font headingFont = FontFactory.getFont(FontFactory.HELVETICA_BOLD, 12);
                document.add(new Paragraph(" "));
                document.add(new Paragraph(file.getPath(), headingFont));
                document.add(new Paragraph(" "));

                // Get highlighted code in HTML format
                String highlightedCode = highlighter.highlightCode(file);

                // Convert HTML to PDF content
                XMLWorkerHelper.getInstance().parseXHtml(writer, document, 
                    new StringReader("<html><body>" + highlightedCode + "</body></html>"));

            } catch (Exception e) {
                document.add(new Paragraph("Error processing file: " + file.getPath() + 
                    " - " + e.getMessage()));
            }
        }

        document.close();
    }

    private void addTableOfContents(Document document, List<File> files) throws DocumentException {
        Font tocFont = FontFactory.getFont(FontFactory.HELVETICA, 12);
        Font tocTitleFont = FontFactory.getFont(FontFactory.HELVETICA_BOLD, 14);

        document.add(new Paragraph("Table of Contents", tocTitleFont));
        document.add(new Paragraph(" "));

        for (File file : files) {
            document.add(new Paragraph(file.getPath(), tocFont));
        }

        document.add(new Paragraph(" "));
        document.add(new Paragraph("---", tocFont));
        document.add(new Paragraph(" "));
    }
}
```

## Required Dependencies

For this implementation, you'll need to add these dependencies to your project:

For Maven (pom.xml):
```xml
<dependencies>
    <!-- iText Core -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.itextpdf</groupId>
        <artifactId>itextpdf</artifactId>
        <version>5.5.13.3</version>
    </dependency>

    <!-- XML Worker for HTML to PDF -->
    <dependency>
        <groupId>com.itextpdf.tool</groupId>
        <artifactId>xmlworker</artifactId>
        <version>5.5.13.3</version>
    </dependency>
</dependencies>
```

